creating ets model ( MAM , MAdM , MNM , auto ) & ARIMA model

fit <- myseries_train %>%
  model(
    MAM = ETS(Turnover ~ error("M") + trend("A") + season("M")),
    MAdM = ETS(Turnover ~ error("M") + trend("Ad") + season("M")),
    MNM = ETS(Turnover ~ error("M") + trend("N") + season("M")),
    auto = ETS(Turnover))

For the choosing of appropriate ARIMA & ETS model , first we create the auto method which r comput by optimizing the lowest aic value, Then we create a shortlist of ARIMA & ETS model to check for their AIC , RMSE

for ARIMA , from the myseries plot we know that there is a need of log transformation and to 1 time seasonal differencing & 1 time differencing , from the ACf & PACF plot , we could see there are some significant lag with seasonallity of 12 months , so we use ARIMA(0,1,2)(0,1,2)[12] , ARIMA(0,1,2)(1,1,1)[12] , ARIMA(1,1,1)(1,1,1)[12]

for ets , looking at the myseries plot , we could conclude that there is a multiplicative error & seasonality , so we use ETS(MAM), ETS(MAdM), ETS(MNM)

comparing the AIC of both models , we could see that ARIMA(0,1,2)(0,1,2)[12] have the lowest AIC in ARIMA while ETS(MNM) has the lowest AIC value in ETS , but looking at myseries plot , we could conclude that there is a trend part in the plot , so we conclude that ETS(MAM) is better

After applying the model to the test set ,

After applying the model to the test set , for the ARIMA(0,1,2)(0,1,2)[12] has the lowest RMSE in the ARIMA method , so we conclude that this is indeed the best ARIMA method for the data , while for the ETS method MAdM has lower RMSE but higher AIC , using this as a consideration , we still choose the ETS(MAM) as the better method as wed probably go with the ETS(M,A,M) model, simply because we expected think turnover will continue to increase due to population increases.

From the data above , we could see the parameter estimates for each model , & looking at the residual diagnostic , we could see that both of them still has some significant lag , this meant the model has not completely solved the autocorrelation issues & the residual is also not normally distributed.It is also shown from the Ljung box test stats with both of them under 0.1 significance level , has lower p value , so the error is significant. On the other side , if we look at the value of the ACF plot , we could see that the value is relatively small (close to 0.1) , this also means that the model that a relatively good job managing the errors.

Looking at the forecast above , we could say that both of the model did a pretty good job in forecasting the 2018 - 2019 data , they both capture the seasonal pattern which it goes up at the end of the year , & start declining while reaching a new year. The also somewhat capture the movement of the data in the early month of the year. Looking at the RMSE , ARIMA this time did a slightly better job than ETS , but both of them still has lower RMSE , which means thet did capture a lot of the data for the forecast.

  1. Discuss the Benefits & limitations of the model

Both arima with drift and EST models fit data very accurate and produce sufficient prediction with confident interval. They also capture the seasonal movement of the data & could implement it to the forecast. If there is no sudden movement in the trend , the model will be a good predictor to use. But as they both has non-independent residulas, other predictions could be less effective , another problem is they cannot capture a sudden movement in the data , like if we actually include the data of 2020, the Turnover declined a lot due to covid-19 , but our model will not predict the arrival of covid-19 , making the model will be a really bad predictor if we include the 2020 data.
